<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06040f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06040f">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06040f"> 40(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> snifs, laughs, ran with / butterbrot</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Et il semble que c&apos;est pr&eacute;cis&eacute;ment dans cette exub&eacute;rance due &agrave; l&apos;exc&egrave;s de force vitale que se rencontre l&apos;origine des jeux. &ldquo;Regardons, dit Karl M&uuml;ller, un petit gar&ccedil;on bien portant qui, tenant dans sa main <mark>une tartine de beurre, se pr&eacute;cipite au dehors</mark>; il laisse, comme l&apos;observation nous le montre, <mark>&eacute;clater une joie pu&eacute;ruile</mark> &agrave; propos de l&apos;objet r&eacute;jouissant qu&apos;il tient en sa main, et cette joie s&apos;exprimera souvent en mouvement et bruit, m&ecirc;me en chants, et cela d&apos;autant plus que ses sentiments et son temp&eacute;rament seront plus vifs. M&ecirc;me &agrave; un &acirc;ge avanc&eacute;, on en vient, en cas d&apos;excitation joyeuse, sinon &agrave; chanter, du moins &agrave; <mark>siffler</mark> &hellip;. <font color="green">[And it seems that it is precisely in this exuberance due to the excess of vital force that the origin of the games is encountered. &ldquo;Look,&rdquo; said Karl M&uuml;ller, &ldquo;a healthy little boy who, holding in his hand a slice of butter, rushes out; he leaves, as the observation shows us, to burst a puerile joy about the joyful object which he holds in his hand, and this joy will often express itself in movement and noise, even in songs, and that of as much as his feelings and temperament will be more lively. Even at an advanced age, it comes, in case of joyous excitement, if not to sing, at least to whistle &hellip;]</font> <small> Fr&eacute;d&eacute;ric Queyrat, <a name="FQLJ" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FQLJ"><cite title="source">Les Jeux des Enfants</cite></a> (1920) 30-1</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
